Nope, @guntersaxenhammer6526 is correct. Powell knew how the world worked, he should have done, seeing as it was him and generations of empire-builders like him that caused the problem in the first place using good old fashioned British plunder, slavery, war-profiteering and corporate manipulation. 

As for the so-called Rivers Of Blood speech, Powell wrote it because he craved power and needed working class votes, and so he sought political allies in deprived areas and scapegoated immigrants from our own colonies, people who had a right to be here, using lies and fake stories about excrement being posted through letterboxes, directly equating blacks with human waste. He knew he was lying but he carried on regardless. The speech in question quite rightly got him disowned by his long-term political allies and friends who saw right through his cheap distortion of the complex reality on the ground in quest of a cheap populist power-grab.

@sebastianriemer1777 Very Little if any. Powell was not in the public life before Orwell died, and Orwell wrote mostly about literary and political circles and general affairs, not much of academics and linguists that Powell was at the time.

And Orwell, well, died the very year Powell entered national politics and he was not yet considered such a prophet of how Soviet communism would turn out during Powell's career.

So they had very little to say about each other. Something poetic really, one prophet extinguishing while another one rises.
